  comment = {Derives information-theoretic framework for active learning in Gaussian models. - When noise is Gaussian, this corresponds to uncertainty sampling (searchwhere parameters unknown). - Shows minimizing posterior uncertainty is the same as maximizing cross-entropy. - Considers second objective: average marginal uncertainty (as opposed to total posterior uncertainty) about a collection of selected points - won't "run away from the data" so much. - For linear Gaussian model with Gaussian prior, doesn't depend on response. (Also true for non-Gaussian prior?) - third, looks at optimal learning for model selection. Gets asymptotic expression that one should test where mu1 and mu2 disagree and sig1 and sig2 are small. (Should rederive this). Doesn't handle EB (continuous hyperparameter) case. related: Seeger07, Steinke07, Chaloner95},
